#week-title("Two", "Stibnite: Safety, Sourcing & The Vinegar of Antimony")

=== Core Teaching

Before any practical antimony work proceeds, the safety requirements of
Safety Document E.3 must be fully understood and confirmed in place. This
is non-negotiable and is confirmed by the headmaster before this week's
laboratory work begins.

*Stibnite (Sb₂S₃).* Raw antimony trisulfide ore is grey-black, often showing
brilliant metallic crystalline habit (long prismatic or acicular crystals).
It is dense — considerably heavier than most common rocks — and has a
characteristic metallic lustre. When fresh, the surface is bright; when
exposed to air over time, it oxidises to a duller grey.

Stibnite can be sourced from mineralogical suppliers, lapidary suppliers, and
specimen dealers. Chinese stibnite (from Hunan province) is the most commonly
available and is appropriate for laboratory work. Confirm purity with the
supplier if possible; avoid specimens coated with artificial enhancements.

*Antimony trioxide (Sb₂O₃).* When stibnite is roasted or heated in air,
antimony trioxide is produced. This is the primary hazardous compound generated
during calcination. It is classified as a possible human carcinogen (Group 2B,
IARC). All heating of stibnite — including the gentle heating required for the
Vinegar preparation — must be conducted with full ventilation and respiratory
protection (P100 minimum).

*The Vinegar of Antimony — first preparation.* The simplest and most accessible
antimony preparation is the extraction of a sour, acidic fraction from raw
stibnite using distilled water at a gentle elevated temperature. This is a wet
extraction rather than a calcination: the stibnite is placed in distilled water
and warmed gently (water bath temperature — no higher than 80°C for the initial
extraction) for several hours. The resulting liquid, filtered and collected, is
the Vinegar of Antimony in its most dilute and accessible form.

This preparation does not require open flame calcination. At water bath
temperatures, minimal volatile antimony compounds are generated. Standard
nitrile gloves and safety glasses are the minimum PPE; working near an open
window is advisable.

#lab[
  *Vinegar of Antimony — Initial Protocol*
  + *Sourcing:* Obtain 10–20g of raw stibnite. Inspect and photograph.
  + *Grinding:* Reduce to coarse powder in a dedicated mortar (never shared
    with food use). Work slowly; dust is an inhalation hazard. Wear N95 or
    better during grinding.
  + *Extraction:* Place powdered stibnite in a glass flask. Cover with
    five times its weight in distilled water. Seal loosely.
  + *Gentle warming:* Water bath, 60–80°C, for 3–4 hours. The water will
    take on a faint yellowish or grey tint.
  + *Filter:* Pour through a paper filter. The filtrate is the Vinegar
    fraction. The solid residue is retained for later calcination work.
  + *Taste (micro-quantity, extreme caution):* With a freshly washed wetted
    fingertip, touch the filtrate and taste. Note the quality: acidic?
    metallic? astringent? Compare with wine vinegar from Year Two Month 10.
  + *Store* in dark glass, labelled: "Vinegar of Antimony — date — source."
]

=== Topics This Week

- Stibnite identification, sourcing, and safe storage
- The hierarchy of hazard: raw handling vs. cold grinding vs. heated work
- The Vinegar of Antimony: the gentlest first extraction
- Sensory comparison: mineral vinegar vs. vegetable vinegar

#inner-work[
  *Confronting the Grey Wolf*

  Before beginning the practical work, sit with a piece of raw stibnite
  (gloved) for ten minutes. Attend to its weight, its surface, its
  particular quality of metallic darkness.

  Record: what quality of awareness does this mineral evoke? Compare with
  the metal meditations of Year Two Month 11. How is the experience of
  stibnite different from lead, from iron, from copper?
]

